value: The spot I picked made it so that even if the other player tried to block me I could still win with different moves.

I saw that it was necessary for X to just about win twice before coming to a situation where there was an open space on both sides of a set of four X's. There was only one space for that to happen. Then O was forced to block the first set of four X's. Then there was another play by X, and only one place for O to go to block the second set of four X's. Then X had two places to go to win and O couldn't block both.

The goal is to build four in a row with an open spot on either side. The instruction said that X needed three moves to win, so the \goal\ as described above would have to be created by the second move. The first move, then, had to set that up, and the way you set up a move is by placing four in a row, forcing O to block the Tic-Tac-Toe. Everything else should be obvious from my practice grid, though I should note that I saw the spot without having to use the practice grid.
There were two areas that already had 3 X's connected so I was trying to see If I could place X's so that if one got blocked off the other would still be able to get to five.

Tried to determine how my moves would increase my chance of forming and open ended row of four while force the other player to make moves that would have to block a closed row of four I did not need but not a potentially open row (I think I over thought it!)

I was looking for a space that would force o to react to my move and block me since they would have been able to get to 4 spaces otherwise. I also was looking for a way to set up multiple avenues of winning that couldn't be blocked.
I bridged the gap between my pieces making them stronger together and manipulated where circle would have to place it's pieces, if it didn't want to lose.
I looked at every section in which the x had at least two consecutive x's. I also looked for a section in which the O might attempt to put an O and focus on winning instead of blocking my strategy.

At first, I just started clicking near spaces with more x's. Figured that would give me the best chance. Tried a couple of different squares, but kept going over 3 turns. Finally moved over to the cluster of x's on the left, and tried different squares there. Once I found something that worked in 3 turns, I tried a couple more times to verify what I believed to be the correct answer.
I tried a few variations of moves and discovered that playing c5 as the first move forced a win.
If X moves at c5 first, O has to block the diagonal win. But then in two more moves, X can get a guaranteed vertical win because of this.
